cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Problem with Brute Force\n> 📖 *From Algorithms Ch. 8:* Brute force search can often be slow or infeasible when there are lots of possibilities. However, **backtracking** can drastically cut down the number of possibilities.\n\nWe want to find a $3 \\times 3$ **magic square** using the digits 1-9 without repetition. A magic square has all rows, columns, and diagonals summing to exactly 15.\n\nIf we use 9 nested loops, we check $9! = 362,880$ arrangements.\nBut if we fill the top row with `[1, 2, 3]`, the sum is 6. This row will *never* sum to 15, no matter what we put in the other 6 squares! \n\n### Backtracking\nWhenever we reach an arrangement that can no longer become valid, we **skip** exploring it further. We use a `continue` statement to jump to the next iteration of the loop, effectively pruning thousands of hopeless branches at once."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. If the top row is `[8, 1, x]`, what must `x` be for the row to sum to 15?\n2. If we prune a branch at the 3rd nested loop out of 9, how many loop iterations did we just save?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. `x = 6`.\n2. We saved $6! = 720$ iterations that would have explored the remaining 6 variables uselessly.\n</details>"),
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase 0 — Math Foundation Practice\n\n### 🎯 Your Turn: Identify Hopeless States\nWrite a function that checks if a fully populated row/col/diag sums to 15. If it is fully populated and does NOT sum to 15, it's hopeless."),
